00:54:39.610 --> 00:54:46.160
There are different strands
of utopianism in Brazil.

00:54:46.160 --> 00:54:50.990
So, one of them is this
egalitarian horizontal view

00:54:50.990 --> 00:54:54.690
of society that is present,
for instance, in the conception

00:54:54.690 --> 00:54:58.260
of laziness and leisure, Brazil
as a country, that is able

00:54:58.260 --> 00:55:00.130
to provide for everyone
so people won't have

00:55:00.130 --> 00:55:01.430
to work and so and so on.

00:55:01.430 --> 00:55:03.120
So, that's one strand.

00:55:03.120 --> 00:55:08.450
Now the messianic strands of
utopian, which comes directly

00:55:08.450 --> 00:55:13.690
from theology, always has an
authoritarian streak to it.

00:55:13.690 --> 00:55:15.950
even if we think about one

00:55:15.950 --> 00:55:22.600
of the most famous messianic
real life experiments in Brazil,

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:25.700
which was described, as I
mentioned, by [inaudible]

00:55:25.700 --> 00:55:29.610
in the Back Lands, famous
book, which [inaudible] Brazil

00:55:29.610 --> 00:55:32.790
where he describes
a community living

00:55:32.790 --> 00:55:34.320
in the back lands of Brazil.

00:55:34.320 --> 00:55:38.200
The leader of this
community, Antonio [inaudible],

00:55:38.200 --> 00:55:43.900
he was what we would call today
really an authoritarian leader

00:55:43.900 --> 00:55:46.360
within this community, right?

00:55:46.360 --> 00:55:49.310
So, I think that
[inaudible] harks back

00:55:49.310 --> 00:55:55.190
to that particular strand of
utopian thought that goes back

00:55:55.190 --> 00:55:58.590
to the messianic tradition
and to authoritarianism

00:55:58.590 --> 00:56:01.210
within the messianic
tradition, right?

00:56:01.210 --> 00:56:06.670
And what I was suggesting is
that I think he has been able

00:56:06.670 --> 00:56:12.500
to activate something that has
been part of a Brazilian culture

00:56:12.500 --> 00:56:16.690
for a very long time, which
is this thinking of messianism

00:56:16.690 --> 00:56:20.030
and the savior that will come
and make everything right.

00:56:20.030 --> 00:56:23.770
And this savior often has
authoritarian characteristics.

00:56:23.770 --> 00:56:25.550
I mean, historically.

00:56:25.550 --> 00:56:28.880
And so people tend to
accept his authoritarianism

00:56:28.880 --> 00:56:32.390
because there are other examples
in Brazilian history of this.

00:56:32.390 --> 00:56:34.820
And, so, it jus t-- he
falls back onto something

00:56:34.820 --> 00:56:37.910
that already exists in the
culture and that's why, I think,

00:56:37.910 --> 00:56:40.970
he's so accepted and
so popular really.

